1
00:00:00,040 --> 00:00:02,140
Over the past dozen or so lessons,

2
00:00:02,140 --> 00:00:05,109
and have covered all sorts of fundamental concepts in neural networks.

3
00:00:05,109 --> 00:00:06,769
We've basically mastered the ultimate weapon.

4
00:00:06,769 --> 00:00:08,389
So, starting with this video,

5
00:00:08,389 --> 00:00:10,240
we're going to start learning about

6
00:00:10,240 --> 00:00:13,120
a framework specifically designed for computer vision tasks.

7
00:00:13,120 --> 00:00:13,800
the CNN,

8
00:00:13,800 --> 00:00:16,310
commonly known as Convolutional Neural Networks.

9
00:00:16,310 --> 00:00:19,110
So first, let's talk about what computer vision tasks actually are.

10
00:00:19,110 --> 00:00:22,390
So, computer vision is essentially about getting machines to understand images.

11
00:00:22,390 --> 00:00:23,590
For us humans,

12
00:00:23,590 --> 00:00:26,110
recognizing an image is a piece of cake.

13
00:00:26,110 --> 00:00:27,430
But for a computer,

14
00:00:27,430 --> 00:00:29,430
an image, in its essence, is just a collection of numbers.

15
00:00:29,430 --> 00:00:33,099
Specifically, the RGB values corresponding to each pixel.

16
00:00:33,099 --> 00:00:35,159
Now, what if we make some slight changes to the image?

17
00:00:35,159 --> 00:00:36,339
For instance, if we change the angle,

18
00:00:36,339 --> 00:00:39,039
adjust the lighting, or cover up a part of it.

19
00:00:39,039 --> 00:00:41,260
To us, it doesn't look all that different.

20
00:00:41,260 --> 00:00:42,700
So, it still seems pretty straightforward.

21
00:00:42,700 --> 00:00:44,060
But for a computer,

22
00:00:44,060 --> 00:00:46,780
the distribution of these pixels has changed dramatically.

23
00:00:46,780 --> 00:00:48,460
it's no longer recognizable.

24
00:00:48,460 --> 00:00:51,100
So, this really gets to the heart of the matter with CV, or Computer Vision.

25
00:00:51,100 --> 00:00:52,820
is not about processing these pixels directly.

26
00:00:52,820 --> 00:00:57,170
Instead, its core purpose is to extract meaningful information from that raw visual data.

27
00:00:57,170 --> 00:00:59,630
to achieve an understanding similar to the human visual system.

28
00:00:59,630 --> 00:01:01,019
judge and reason.

29
00:01:01,019 --> 00:01:04,299
Its core tasks, some of the most common ones, include image classification.

30
00:01:04,299 --> 00:01:05,579
Give us an image,

31
00:01:05,579 --> 00:01:08,850
and ask us to figure out what the main subject in the picture is.

32
00:01:08,850 --> 00:01:11,130
Then there's object detection, which, within an image,

33
00:01:11,130 --> 00:01:12,130
like people, cars,

34
00:01:12,130 --> 00:01:13,600
and traffic lights等各种目标标注出来。

35
00:01:13,600 --> 00:01:14,920
And then there's image segmentation.

36
00:01:14,920 --> 00:01:17,520
It separates the road, the sky, and the pedestrians pixel by pixel.

37
00:01:17,520 --> 00:01:18,420
the detection of human faces,

38
00:01:18,420 --> 00:01:19,880
This is something we use a lot.

39
00:01:19,880 --> 00:01:22,800
OCR, or Optical Character Recognition, extracts text from images.

40
00:01:22,800 --> 00:01:24,480
or even autonomous driving in cars.

41
00:01:24,480 --> 00:01:25,840
and it's also used in image processing.

42
00:01:25,840 --> 00:01:27,320
Here we have a picture of a cat.

43
00:01:27,320 --> 00:01:29,960
So, what if we keep zooming in on this picture?

44
00:01:29,960 --> 00:01:32,920
At first, you can still zoom in smoothly and continuously.

45
00:01:32,920 --> 00:01:35,600
we'll start to see this kind of pixelated style.

46
00:01:35,600 --> 00:01:37,950
or mosaic-like grid cells.

47
00:01:37,950 --> 00:01:41,590
So, in reality, an image is just made up of a huge number of these tiny squares.

48
00:01:41,590 --> 00:01:44,000
They are arranged one by one in a specific order.

49
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:46,720
And each of these small grids is actually a block of color.

50
00:01:46,720 --> 00:01:49,400
And each one of these represents a color.

51
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:51,980
And we call this color block a pixel.

52
00:01:51,980 --> 00:01:55,220
It stores the color information for that specific location in the image.

53
00:01:55,220 --> 00:01:58,460
So, how do we actually represent this color?

54
00:01:58,460 --> 00:01:59,720
Why is this color brown,

55
00:01:59,720 --> 00:02:00,950
This is red,

56
00:02:00,950 --> 00:02:02,250
This one's magenta or something like that.

57
00:02:02,250 --> 00:02:03,050
So, how is this expressed?

58
00:02:03,050 --> 00:02:06,210
We also often see that RGB corresponds to three numbers.

59
00:02:06,210 --> 00:02:07,820
So, what are these?

60
00:02:07,820 --> 00:02:10,920
So, let's take a look at how computers actually represent color.

61
00:02:10,920 --> 00:02:13,100
In nature, there are countless colors.

62
00:02:13,100 --> 00:02:16,170
But obviously, a computer can't just assign a unique code to every single possible color.

63
00:02:16,170 --> 00:02:19,070
In reality, within a computer, color is defined by something called RGB.

64
00:02:19,070 --> 00:02:20,470
—stands for Red, Green, and Blue.

65
00:02:20,470 --> 00:02:24,200
These three primary colors are also known as the three primary colors.

66
00:02:24,200 --> 00:02:26,140
By arranging and combining these three colors,

67
00:02:26,140 --> 00:02:29,000
a vast array of colors can be produced.

68
00:02:29,160 --> 00:02:30,560
Now, let's take a look at this diagram.

69
00:02:30,560 --> 00:02:31,460
If it's just red light,

70
00:02:31,460 --> 00:02:32,500
green light, and blue light.

71
00:02:32,500 --> 00:02:34,080
and for this one, we adjust its brightness

72
00:02:34,080 --> 00:02:35,720
That is, it ranges from 0 to 255.

73
00:02:38,870 --> 00:02:40,019
This is a solid color.

74
00:02:40,019 --> 00:02:42,779
So, what if we start to mix red and green?

75
00:02:42,779 --> 00:02:43,859
it will actually create yellow.

76
00:02:43,859 --> 00:02:45,520
And it's the same in the natural world.

77
00:02:45,520 --> 00:02:48,740
Different combinations of these colors will produce new ones.

78
00:02:48,740 --> 00:02:51,630
So, if we make all three colors fully bright,

79
00:02:51,630 --> 00:02:52,930
all set to 255,

80
00:02:52,930 --> 00:02:54,350
you get pure white.

81
00:02:54,350 --> 00:02:56,080
It's kind of like how a rainbow works.

82
00:02:56,080 --> 00:02:58,200
It's just breaking down the color white.

83
00:02:58,200 --> 00:02:59,620
So this is how we put it back together.

84
00:02:59,620 --> 00:03:01,280
If all three colors are dark,

85
00:03:01,280 --> 00:03:01,720
and they're all zero

86
00:03:01,720 --> 00:03:02,320
So what does that look like?

87
00:03:02,320 --> 00:03:03,600
That would be pure black.

88
00:03:03,600 --> 00:03:07,240
So, every color can be represented by these three RGB values.

89
00:03:07,240 --> 00:03:09,640
And each of these numbers represents the brightness of its respective color channel.

90
00:03:09,640 --> 00:03:13,260
And by combining values from 0 to 255, we can create all sorts of different colors.

91
00:03:13,460 --> 00:03:16,350
For example, pure red would be 255,

92
00:03:16,350 --> 00:03:17,590
And all the others are zero.

93
00:03:17,590 --> 00:03:20,210
So for pure black, we just covered that it's zero.

94
00:03:20,210 --> 00:03:22,270
and for black, it's all 255s.

95
00:03:22,270 --> 00:03:23,269
that's white.

96
00:03:23,269 --> 00:03:25,549
And if we look closely, we'll notice something.

97
00:03:25,549 --> 00:03:27,929
Now, if the RGB values are all equal,

98
00:03:27,929 --> 00:03:29,229
for example, all at 255,

99
00:03:29,229 --> 00:03:29,929
or zero,

100
00:03:29,929 --> 00:03:32,670
or maybe they're all 128, something like that.

101
00:03:32,670 --> 00:03:34,750
So, you'll find that when these three color values are equal,

102
00:03:34,750 --> 00:03:36,210
you'll get a shade of gray.

103
00:03:36,210 --> 00:03:37,190
If all of them are zero,

104
00:03:37,190 --> 00:03:38,050
then it becomes black.

105
00:03:38,050 --> 00:03:39,920
And if it's all 255, it becomes white.

106
00:03:39,920 --> 00:03:41,440
What if it's 121, 128?

107
00:03:41,440 --> 00:03:42,820
It would be a shade of gray in the middle.

108
00:03:42,820 --> 00:03:43,720
And that's a circle.

109
00:03:43,720 --> 00:03:47,910
So, a computer can represent any color using just three sets of numbers.

110
00:03:47,910 --> 00:03:50,650
So, that's how we process color images.

111
00:03:50,650 --> 00:03:52,230
So, let's say for example, we're given a...

112
00:03:52,230 --> 00:03:54,150
a 32 by 32 color image.

113
00:03:54,150 --> 00:03:55,170
So, what does that mean?

114
00:03:55,170 --> 00:03:57,730
So, it just means there are 32 pixels horizontally.

115
00:03:57,730 --> 00:03:59,390
It doesn't matter if we're talking about the length or the width.

116
00:03:59,390 --> 00:04:00,230
But that's not important.

117
00:04:00,230 --> 00:04:02,250
You have 32 pixels horizontally,

118
00:04:02,250 --> 00:04:04,709
And vertically, it also has 32 pixels.

119
00:04:04,709 --> 00:04:09,530
And each of these pixels is represented by three values: Red, Green, and Blue, or RGB.

120
00:04:09,530 --> 00:04:11,890
So, if we're processing an image on a computer,

121
00:04:11,890 --> 00:04:14,170
a 32 by 32 color image,

122
00:04:14,170 --> 00:04:15,560
it would be written as three channels.

123
00:04:15,560 --> 00:04:17,060
the RGB channels.

124
00:04:17,060 --> 00:04:19,120
where each channel is a 32 by 32 grid.

125
00:04:19,120 --> 00:04:20,060
It's a two-dimensional array.

126
00:04:20,060 --> 00:04:22,040
So essentially, it's a three-dimensional tensor overall.

127
00:04:22,040 --> 00:04:24,350
or a three-dimensional array, and that's what we get.

128
00:04:24,350 --> 00:04:26,750
But as I mentioned before, for gray-scale images...

129
00:04:26,750 --> 00:04:28,430
That's because all three of its color channels are identical.

130
00:04:28,430 --> 00:04:30,870
So, there's no need to distinguish between the three channels.

131
00:04:30,870 --> 00:04:31,790
So you just give it a single channel.

132
00:04:31,790 --> 00:04:33,150
So in this case, it's 32 by 32.

133
00:04:33,150 --> 00:04:36,090
So, it can be represented by just a two-dimensional matrix.

134
00:04:36,090 --> 00:04:37,390
Let's take a look.

135
00:04:37,390 --> 00:04:40,650
Before, when we used the MNIST handwritten digits dataset,

136
00:04:40,650 --> 00:04:42,290
So, it's essentially a grayscale image.

137
00:04:42,290 --> 00:04:43,290
And the numbers on it,

138
00:04:43,290 --> 00:04:46,650
represented by either white or some shade of gray in between.

139
00:04:46,650 --> 00:04:48,590
So, its representation is a two-dimensional array.

140
00:04:48,590 --> 00:04:50,750
Now, these numbers aren't set in stone;

141
00:04:50,750 --> 00:04:53,289
It's just meant as an illustration to show how it's represented.

142
00:04:53,289 --> 00:04:55,129
For instance, take the MNIST dataset we use.

143
00:04:55,129 --> 00:04:56,369
are all 28 by 28.

144
00:04:56,369 --> 00:04:58,460
That means there are 28 points horizontally,

145
00:04:58,460 --> 00:04:59,940
and 28 points vertically.

146
00:04:59,940 --> 00:05:04,509
And each of these points is represented by a numerical value, typically ranging from 0 to 1.

147
00:05:04,509 --> 00:05:06,429
The darker areas gradually get larger and more resemble white.

148
00:05:06,429 --> 00:05:07,809
As you can see, the center is white.

149
00:05:07,809 --> 00:05:08,549
So it's pretty much the same.

150
00:05:08,549 --> 00:05:10,530
So basically, that's what it means.

151
00:05:10,530 --> 00:05:11,490
so we can just use one channel

152
00:05:11,490 --> 00:05:13,050
Because the color values in all three channels are the same.

153
00:05:13,050 --> 00:05:15,210
So, I can just use one channel to represent it.

154
00:05:15,210 --> 00:05:16,770
that tells you how bright it is.

155
00:05:16,770 --> 00:05:18,350
The brightest is 255.

156
00:05:18,350 --> 00:05:19,370
So, we know that...

157
00:05:19,370 --> 00:05:21,470
So that's why, when we were talking about MLPs,

158
00:05:21,470 --> 00:05:22,270
Do you all remember?

159
00:05:22,270 --> 00:05:25,020
and you might be wondering where this number 784 comes from.

160
00:05:25,020 --> 00:05:27,860
So, 28 times 28 gives you 784.

161
00:05:27,860 --> 00:05:30,640
This represents how many numbers are used for each pixel.

162
00:05:30,640 --> 00:05:32,300
What about for a color image?

163
00:05:32,300 --> 00:05:34,760
Now, we know that a color image has three channels.

164
00:05:34,760 --> 00:05:37,280
We can represent this as three arrays.

165
00:05:37,280 --> 00:05:38,600
forming three two-dimensional arrays.

166
00:05:38,600 --> 00:05:41,830
So, it's really just a three-dimensional tensor.

167
00:05:41,830 --> 00:05:43,850
This arranges them so that the top part is all red.

168
00:05:43,850 --> 00:05:45,590
and the intensity values for the red channel,

169
00:05:45,590 --> 00:05:46,230
the green channel,

170
00:05:46,230 --> 00:05:47,660
and the blue channel.

171
00:05:47,660 --> 00:05:50,480
And just like that, you get an RGB array.

172
00:05:50,480 --> 00:05:52,180
and feeds it a three-dimensional array.

173
00:05:52,180 --> 00:05:54,409
and that's how you get a full-color image.

174
00:05:54,409 --> 00:05:56,750
But, for a 32 by 32 image,

175
00:05:56,750 --> 00:05:58,170
you would then multiply that by three.

176
00:05:58,170 --> 00:06:00,370
So that's a total of 3072 values.

177
00:06:00,370 --> 00:06:03,810
Alright, now that we've got a handle on how images are represented,

178
00:06:03,810 --> 00:06:05,520
Actually, when we were working with handwritten digits,

179
00:06:05,520 --> 00:06:07,400
to have a computer recognize handwritten digits,

180
00:06:07,400 --> 00:06:10,360
and we were already able to successfully recognize it using an MLP.

181
00:06:10,360 --> 00:06:13,600
And if we then combine that with learning rate scheduling and parameter initialization,

182
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:14,100
normalization,

183
00:06:14,100 --> 00:06:16,570
and other training optimization techniques like regularization,

184
00:06:16,570 --> 00:06:18,570
the accuracy of this handwritten digit recognition,

185
00:06:18,570 --> 00:06:20,190
We've already hit 98%.

186
00:06:20,190 --> 00:06:22,469
So, what if I were to tweak this a bit?

187
00:06:22,469 --> 00:06:24,589
to have it recognize whether there's a dog or a cat in the picture.

188
00:06:24,589 --> 00:06:26,980
Or have it mark out the roads.

189
00:06:26,980 --> 00:06:28,100
Wouldn't that also work?

190
00:06:28,100 --> 00:06:30,100
But what about using the MLP approach?

191
00:06:30,100 --> 00:06:30,940
Deep neural networks...

192
00:06:30,940 --> 00:06:32,800
like, by making the network a bit deeper.

193
00:06:32,800 --> 00:06:34,780
So, can it handle more complex tasks?

194
00:06:34,780 --> 00:06:35,840
Actually, that doesn't work.

195
00:06:35,840 --> 00:06:36,919
So, why is that?

196
00:06:36,919 --> 00:06:38,279
What about for something like the MNIST dataset?

197
00:06:38,279 --> 00:06:38,819
isn't too bad.

198
00:06:38,819 --> 00:06:39,279
So, why is that?

199
00:06:39,279 --> 00:06:41,839
Because it's a 28 by 28 grayscale image.

200
00:06:41,839 --> 00:06:43,519
So, when you convert it into a matrix,

201
00:06:43,519 --> 00:06:44,639
So, it has 28 rows in total,

202
00:06:44,639 --> 00:06:46,400
and 28 columns, making 784 pixels in total.

203
00:06:46,400 --> 00:06:47,400
So, when we process it,

204
00:06:47,400 --> 00:06:48,720
What we're actually doing is flattening it.

205
00:06:48,720 --> 00:06:49,780
rather than treating it as a two-dimensional object.

206
00:06:49,780 --> 00:06:52,080
Because we're treating it as 784 individual features.

207
00:06:52,080 --> 00:06:53,440
and feed it into the neural network.

208
00:06:53,440 --> 00:06:56,499
So, from X1 to X784, it goes to the second layer.

209
00:06:56,499 --> 00:06:57,699
and that's it for the third layer.

210
00:06:57,699 --> 00:06:59,819
So, what about the hidden layer? Let's break it down.

211
00:06:59,819 --> 00:07:02,530
So, if it only has 784 features, it's still manageable.

212
00:07:02,530 --> 00:07:04,730
This is especially true for modern computers.

213
00:07:04,730 --> 00:07:05,970
it can still handle it.

214
00:07:05,970 --> 00:07:08,230
So overall, the number of parameters is manageable.

215
00:07:08,230 --> 00:07:10,510
But what about images from the real world?

216
00:07:10,510 --> 00:07:13,070
are far more complex than the images in the MNIST dataset.

217
00:07:13,070 --> 00:07:15,320
So, let's start with something a little more complex.

218
00:07:15,320 --> 00:07:16,320
just a bit bigger.

219
00:07:16,320 --> 00:07:17,480
Let's say 32 by 32.

220
00:07:17,480 --> 00:07:19,040
But... this time, it's a color image.

221
00:07:19,040 --> 00:07:20,680
So, we multiply that by three,

222
00:07:20,680 --> 00:07:23,280
That's about 3,072 pixel values in total.

223
00:07:23,280 --> 00:07:26,120
if we design the second layer to have 512 neurons,

224
00:07:26,120 --> 00:07:28,669
So, in the first layer, after we flatten this small image,

225
00:07:28,669 --> 00:07:30,129
you'd just multiply that by three.

226
00:07:30,129 --> 00:07:31,389
Because, you know, there are three channels.

227
00:07:31,389 --> 00:07:33,269
So for a color image, that's 3072 right there.

228
00:07:33,269 --> 00:07:36,100
So what if we add another hidden layer after that?

229
00:07:36,100 --> 00:07:37,700
and it has 512 neurons,

230
00:07:37,700 --> 00:07:41,460
Then, that would require roughly over a million parameters.

231
00:07:41,460 --> 00:07:42,150
that's already

232
00:07:42,150 --> 00:07:43,710
So, what if we make things a bit more complex?

233
00:07:43,710 --> 00:07:45,150
Now, for the images we use today,

234
00:07:45,150 --> 00:07:45,990
We often talk about...

235
00:07:45,990 --> 00:07:49,070
that our pixel count is 1024 by 768.

236
00:07:49,070 --> 00:07:52,490
Even 1920 by 1080 is considered quite large.

237
00:07:52,490 --> 00:07:54,670
and this is just 224 by 224 pixels.

238
00:07:54,670 --> 00:07:57,100
Now, for modern images, a small picture like this...

239
00:07:57,100 --> 00:07:58,380
is far from being considered clear.

240
00:07:58,380 --> 00:07:59,320
And since it's a color image,

241
00:07:59,320 --> 00:08:00,580
So, after flattening it out...

242
00:08:00,580 --> 00:08:02,830
that's already 150,000 inputs.

243
00:08:02,830 --> 00:08:04,570
And if the second layer also has 512 neurons,

244
00:08:04,570 --> 00:08:07,010
In fact, 512 isn't even that many compared to the first layer.

245
00:08:07,010 --> 00:08:08,800
Multiply that, and you're already at seventy...

246
00:08:08,800 --> 00:08:11,600
And just the first two layers alone would already require over 70 million parameters.

247
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:13,160
Now, for a computer,

248
00:08:13,160 --> 00:08:15,080
especially back in the early days of computing.

249
00:08:15,080 --> 00:08:16,140
This was completely infeasible.

250
00:08:16,140 --> 00:08:17,560
And keep in mind, that's just for the first layer.

251
00:08:17,560 --> 00:08:19,020
and if I multiply that by another layer...

252
00:08:19,020 --> 00:08:20,120
Then it gets even bigger.

253
00:08:20,120 --> 00:08:22,100
So there's just no way I can make it into...

254
00:08:22,100 --> 00:08:23,200
a deep neural network.

255
00:08:23,200 --> 00:08:24,980
It can only handle learning one or two layers at most.

256
00:08:24,980 --> 00:08:27,990
So naturally, the features it learns are going to be very shallow.

257
00:08:27,990 --> 00:08:29,550
So, what can we do about it?

258
00:08:29,550 --> 00:08:32,030
But of course, we've only scratched the surface of its problems.

259
00:08:32,030 --> 00:08:33,650
And it’s not just about having too many parameters.

260
00:08:33,650 --> 00:08:35,860
Having too many parameters is just one of the problems.

261
00:08:35,860 --> 00:08:37,880
They just make the training process much slower.

262
00:08:37,880 --> 00:08:39,320
The strain on memory also increased.

263
00:08:39,320 --> 00:08:43,869
And on top of that, if you have a limited amount of data,

264
00:08:43,869 --> 00:08:45,620
For instance, let's say we don't have enough images.

265
00:08:45,620 --> 00:08:47,720
let's say you only have a few tens of thousands of images

266
00:08:47,720 --> 00:08:49,940
but when my model has over 70 million parameters,

267
00:08:49,940 --> 00:08:53,420
So, with a model like that, it's pretty much guaranteed to overfit as soon as you start training it.

268
00:08:53,420 --> 00:08:54,010
pretty much.

269
00:08:54,010 --> 00:08:55,930
But actually, that's not even its biggest problem.

270
00:08:55,930 --> 00:08:58,290
The MLP can't handle images at its core.

271
00:08:58,290 --> 00:09:00,240
So, what's the real, deeper reason for this?

272
00:09:00,240 --> 00:09:01,280
So, when it comes to images...

273
00:09:01,280 --> 00:09:03,680
Well, even though images are represented in a computer as...

274
00:09:03,680 --> 00:09:05,260
strings of ones and zeros, just like that.

275
00:09:05,260 --> 00:09:08,260
We say it's 255, but that's just us humans converting it into a decimal number.

276
00:09:10,560 --> 00:09:14,120
But an image itself isn't really just a list of independent numbers.

277
00:09:14,120 --> 00:09:15,920
It has a spatial structure.

278
00:09:15,920 --> 00:09:17,200
is related to the pixel in front of it,

279
00:09:17,200 --> 00:09:19,340
is usually related to the pixels that come after it.

280
00:09:19,340 --> 00:09:20,480
that come together to form a person.

281
00:09:20,480 --> 00:09:21,940
They're not randomly distributed.

282
00:09:21,940 --> 00:09:22,380
Right.

283
00:09:22,380 --> 00:09:23,620
And also, think about an image.

284
00:09:23,620 --> 00:09:25,700
In fact, there are a few typical characteristics.

285
00:09:25,700 --> 00:09:26,700
This is called local correlation.

286
00:09:26,700 --> 00:09:29,020
Its pattern only appears within a small, localized area.

287
00:09:29,020 --> 00:09:30,620
It's a gradual transition.

288
00:09:30,620 --> 00:09:32,040
For example, let's say this part here is black.

289
00:09:32,040 --> 00:09:33,520
the surrounding area is also very likely to be black.

290
00:09:33,520 --> 00:09:35,220
as purple starts to gradually appear,

291
00:09:35,220 --> 00:09:36,200
the surrounding area is also purple.

292
00:09:36,200 --> 00:09:37,800
They are related to each other.

293
00:09:37,800 --> 00:09:39,460
Another one is translation equivariance.

294
00:09:39,460 --> 00:09:41,040
Or, as it's also called, translation invariance.

295
00:09:41,040 --> 00:09:41,880
Its position has changed,

296
00:09:41,880 --> 00:09:43,280
the pattern itself remains unchanged.

297
00:09:43,280 --> 00:09:45,360
For example, let's say we move these characters over here.

298
00:09:45,360 --> 00:09:46,630
It's still the same characters.

299
00:09:46,630 --> 00:09:48,350
And another property is its hierarchical structure.

300
00:09:48,350 --> 00:09:50,470
So, we'll break this down together in a moment.

301
00:09:51,590 --> 00:09:53,840
First, let's take a look at local correlation.

302
00:09:53,840 --> 00:09:55,400
Take the meaning of a single pixel, for instance.

303
00:09:55,400 --> 00:09:57,280
is mainly determined by what this pixel represents.

304
00:09:57,280 --> 00:09:58,600
So, once we flatten it,

305
00:09:58,600 --> 00:10:00,460
It loses all connection to its surroundings.

306
00:10:00,460 --> 00:10:03,800
But in reality, the relationship a pixel has with its neighbors is extremely important.

307
00:10:03,800 --> 00:10:05,000
Let's try to recognize something.

308
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:06,280
For example, say we have this picture of a dog.

309
00:10:06,280 --> 00:10:07,220
We can tell that...

310
00:10:07,220 --> 00:10:08,680
For example, when we're looking at this part here,

311
00:10:08,680 --> 00:10:09,720
and we can tell right away.

312
00:10:09,720 --> 00:10:10,820
This is the dog's eye.

313
00:10:10,820 --> 00:10:13,020
It's what's right next to it that helps us make that identification.

314
00:10:13,020 --> 00:10:13,860
Or take the dog's paw, for instance.

315
00:10:13,860 --> 00:10:17,080
So, for instance, does this part of the image affect our ability to recognize the dog's eye?

316
00:10:17,080 --> 00:10:18,600
Not at all. It has no effect whatsoever.

317
00:10:18,600 --> 00:10:22,469
It's only related to the local area around it, its immediate surroundings.

318
00:10:22,469 --> 00:10:23,509
or its nose and mouth.

319
00:10:23,509 --> 00:10:25,360
and it's also connected to the global information.

320
00:10:25,360 --> 00:10:26,340
or the grass next to it.

321
00:10:26,340 --> 00:10:27,160
its legs,

322
00:10:27,160 --> 00:10:30,089
don't really help us much in identifying the eyes.

323
00:10:30,089 --> 00:10:32,009
For example, if we take images from the natural world,

324
00:10:32,009 --> 00:10:33,009
And it's actually the same for all of them.

325
00:10:33,009 --> 00:10:34,389
We can see right away, this is an edge.

326
00:10:34,389 --> 00:10:35,349
And this one is a corner.

327
00:10:35,349 --> 00:10:36,989
It doesn't matter what's next to it.

328
00:10:36,989 --> 00:10:38,920
And this one, that would be animal fur.

329
00:10:38,920 --> 00:10:40,220
And this one looks like it's part of a leaf.

330
00:10:40,220 --> 00:10:41,120
And this right here is the wheel.

331
00:10:41,120 --> 00:10:42,960
Actually, it's related to the car's window,

332
00:10:42,960 --> 00:10:44,480
or this glass, this is a door handle.

333
00:10:44,480 --> 00:10:46,080
realistically, all you need to do is look at the local area.

334
00:10:46,080 --> 00:10:49,520
Pixels that are far away don't really have much to do with it.

335
00:10:49,520 --> 00:10:52,540
But in an MLP, we establish full connections.

336
00:10:52,540 --> 00:10:55,960
essentially, it makes every single pixel relate to all the others.

337
00:10:55,960 --> 00:10:58,109
But in the context of images, that's really not necessary.

338
00:10:58,109 --> 00:10:59,770
This leads to an explosion in the number of parameters.

339
00:10:59,770 --> 00:11:00,770
So, what's the second point?

340
00:11:00,770 --> 00:11:01,750
translation equivariance.

341
00:11:01,750 --> 00:11:04,090
And as I briefly mentioned with that example a moment ago...

342
00:11:04,090 --> 00:11:05,130
the same local pattern

343
00:11:05,130 --> 00:11:07,740
appearing in the top-left corner or the bottom-right corner of an image

344
00:11:07,740 --> 00:11:09,360
essentially, it's the same pattern.

345
00:11:09,360 --> 00:11:11,339
Only their position has changed.

346
00:11:11,339 --> 00:11:14,099
So really, it doesn't need to learn a separate pattern for every single position.

347
00:11:14,099 --> 00:11:16,200
there's no need to train a whole new detection pattern for it.

348
00:11:16,200 --> 00:11:18,900
For example, let's say we have an image of a kitten.

349
00:11:18,900 --> 00:11:21,280
In the top-left corner of the image, we've successfully identified it.

350
00:11:21,280 --> 00:11:22,380
And that it's a cat.

351
00:11:22,380 --> 00:11:24,140
And that actually affects the entire image.

352
00:11:24,140 --> 00:11:25,240
This is called a feature map.

353
00:11:25,240 --> 00:11:26,740
We'll get to that in a moment.

354
00:11:26,740 --> 00:11:27,600
This area is highlighted,

355
00:11:27,600 --> 00:11:29,440
This indicates there's a cat in this region.

356
00:11:29,440 --> 00:11:30,980
The rest of the areas remain dark.

357
00:11:30,980 --> 00:11:32,780
This means there's nothing significant in the rest of the areas.

358
00:11:32,780 --> 00:11:34,900
This can be interpreted as a filter.

359
00:11:34,900 --> 00:11:37,070
For example, let's take a thermal imaging scenario.

360
00:11:37,070 --> 00:11:38,250
Let's say this area has some heat signal.

361
00:11:38,250 --> 00:11:40,940
Only this specific spot lights up, while other areas without heat remain dark.

362
00:11:40,940 --> 00:11:42,180
So, this is what image recognition is all about.

363
00:11:42,180 --> 00:11:44,360
or, you could say, some of the fundamental techniques for signal recognition.

364
00:11:44,360 --> 00:11:47,300
You can also call it pattern detection, or a 'detector', things like that.

365
00:11:47,300 --> 00:11:48,540
So, what about the second picture?

366
00:11:48,540 --> 00:11:50,620
I just need to move the kitten to the bottom-right corner.

367
00:11:50,620 --> 00:11:51,900
it's still the same kitten.

368
00:11:51,900 --> 00:11:54,500
So, I don't actually need to build a whole new detector for that, right?

369
00:11:54,500 --> 00:11:57,920
So, whether we call it a convolutional kernel or a filter later on,

370
00:11:57,920 --> 00:11:59,540
Right, they're just all sorts of signal waves.

371
00:11:59,540 --> 00:12:00,080
There's no need for that.

372
00:12:00,080 --> 00:12:01,120
As long as these two are the same, it'll work.

373
00:12:01,120 --> 00:12:02,020
All I need to do is detect...

374
00:12:02,020 --> 00:12:04,160
In fact, you can just use the same thing to detect it.

375
00:12:04,160 --> 00:12:06,000
It only needs to process this small section, and that's it.

376
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:07,920
But, if you were to use a fully connected network,

377
00:12:07,920 --> 00:12:09,680
you actually have to recognize the entire thing.

378
00:12:09,680 --> 00:12:11,560
and now everything in this block is different.

379
00:12:11,560 --> 00:12:14,070
This results in a huge waste of parameters.

380
00:12:14,070 --> 00:12:17,410
And the third is the hierarchy of high-level semantics within an image.

381
00:12:17,410 --> 00:12:19,340
In fact, it's not generated by a single pixel.

382
00:12:19,340 --> 00:12:22,180
Instead, they are constructed gradually from low-level visual patterns.

383
00:12:22,180 --> 00:12:23,420
So, in general,

384
00:12:23,420 --> 00:12:27,040
We'll also cover this when we get to the low-level details later on.

385
00:12:27,040 --> 00:12:28,940
So, when we try to recognize images,

386
00:12:28,940 --> 00:12:30,300
Although we aren't consciously aware of this process,

387
00:12:30,300 --> 00:12:31,980
But this is what's actually happening.

388
00:12:31,980 --> 00:12:34,740
At first, all we see is this vague, patchy area.

389
00:12:34,740 --> 00:12:35,620
an idea of what it is.

390
00:12:35,620 --> 00:12:37,860
and gradually starts to make out the textures and edges.

391
00:12:37,860 --> 00:12:39,380
and then you can start to make out the different parts.

392
00:12:39,380 --> 00:12:41,800
And gradually, these parts can actually be pieced together into a whole.

393
00:12:41,800 --> 00:12:44,080
In fact, this principle applies to human visual nerves, which are, after all, those of mammals.

394
00:12:44,080 --> 00:12:45,860
The visual nerve works in exactly the same way.

395
00:12:45,860 --> 00:12:49,370
So, at the lower layers, if we process it layer by layer...

396
00:12:49,370 --> 00:12:52,190
At the shallow layers, it primarily looks for some local features.

397
00:12:52,190 --> 00:12:54,770
As we go deeper, it gradually abstracts the features, creating a higher-level representation.

398
00:12:54,770 --> 00:12:57,840
So, if we take this cat's face, an MLP just can't solve these problems.

399
00:12:57,840 --> 00:13:00,340
It flattens the image into a one-dimensional vector.

400
00:13:00,340 --> 00:13:01,860
This completely ignores the local correlations within the image.

401
00:13:01,860 --> 00:13:04,380
Because originally, all the pixels were right next to each other.

402
00:13:04,380 --> 00:13:05,420
once you flatten it out,

403
00:13:05,420 --> 00:13:07,460
so any relationship between them is basically lost.

404
00:13:07,460 --> 00:13:10,030
This completely destroys the image's spatial structure.

405
00:13:10,030 --> 00:13:12,110
If we truly want to process images,

406
00:13:12,110 --> 00:13:13,030
So, how do we go about recognizing images?

407
00:13:13,030 --> 00:13:16,160
What we truly need is something that's well-suited for images.

408
00:13:16,160 --> 00:13:17,620
a network for these kinds of tasks.

409
00:13:17,620 --> 00:13:20,060
one that can adapt to the unique characteristics of images themselves.

410
00:13:20,060 --> 00:13:23,110
And that's exactly what a Convolutional Neural Network, or CNN, is all about.

411
00:13:23,110 --> 00:13:25,510
Its core philosophy can be summed up in one single sentence.

412
00:13:25,510 --> 00:13:26,030
So, why is that?

413
00:13:26,030 --> 00:13:26,790
First, you look at the local parts.

414
00:13:26,790 --> 00:13:31,330
and then gradually piece together the bigger picture. So, what does that mean?

415
00:13:31,330 --> 00:13:32,430
Let's take a look.

416
00:13:32,430 --> 00:13:34,870
Of course, this concept wasn't just pulled out of thin air.

417
00:13:34,870 --> 00:13:37,060
In fact, this idea goes way back to the 1950s.

418
00:13:37,060 --> 00:13:38,380
neuroscientists had actually already...

419
00:13:38,380 --> 00:13:40,140
while studying the visual cortex of cats,

420
00:13:40,140 --> 00:13:41,480
and they discovered a certain pattern.

421
00:13:41,480 --> 00:13:44,200
You see, the visual cortex has a massive number of neurons.

422
00:13:44,200 --> 00:13:47,000
But it turns out, these neurons don't just light up for any image they see.

423
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:48,160
to respond to.

424
00:13:48,160 --> 00:13:50,270
It's only certain neurons,

425
00:13:50,270 --> 00:13:53,330
For instance, some neurons will only respond when they encounter a vertical line.

426
00:13:53,330 --> 00:13:54,960
that it will have a strong reaction.

427
00:13:54,960 --> 00:13:58,520
But when it comes across horizontal lines in an image,

428
00:13:58,520 --> 00:14:00,300
it barely responds at all.

429
00:14:00,300 --> 00:14:03,300
So, if we were to explain this using a neural network...

430
00:14:03,300 --> 00:14:04,620
So after it goes through the activation function,

431
00:14:04,620 --> 00:14:06,120
basically means it doesn't output anything.

432
00:14:06,120 --> 00:14:08,560
But for others, let's say, they are highly sensitive to diagonal lines.

433
00:14:08,560 --> 00:14:09,960
So when you show it a diagonal line like this,

434
00:14:09,960 --> 00:14:11,860
it's not sensitive to it at all.

435
00:14:11,860 --> 00:14:14,260
And of course, these two researchers also made a breakthrough based on this principle.

436
00:14:14,260 --> 00:14:15,800
And later on, they both won the Nobel Prize for it.

437
00:14:15,800 --> 00:14:17,360
In essence, this is what's known as a local receptive field.

438
00:14:17,360 --> 00:14:18,920
In other words, it also only looks at a small patch.

439
00:14:18,920 --> 00:14:20,000
it only focuses on a small patch.

440
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:21,380
whether there are horizontal or vertical lines,

441
00:14:21,380 --> 00:14:22,380
What kind of textures are there?

442
00:14:22,380 --> 00:14:24,260
Now, this is just a simple example to illustrate the point.

443
00:14:24,260 --> 00:14:25,880
and it's being processed layer by layer.

444
00:14:25,880 --> 00:14:26,500
And what about this one?

445
00:14:26,500 --> 00:14:30,270
This actually also influenced how later generations tackled computer vision tasks.

446
00:14:30,270 --> 00:14:31,890
So, I'll start by just looking at a small patch.

447
00:14:31,890 --> 00:14:35,610
and then the deeper layers will take these small pieces and combine them,

448
00:14:35,610 --> 00:14:37,430
to abstract even higher-level features.

449
00:14:37,430 --> 00:14:39,630
And then combine those even further.

450
00:14:39,630 --> 00:14:41,310
and gradually, it all starts to make sense.

451
00:14:41,310 --> 00:14:43,849
And that's pretty much how a CNN works, too.

452
00:14:43,849 --> 00:14:44,749
Of course,

453
00:14:44,749 --> 00:14:45,449
In the early days,

454
00:14:45,449 --> 00:14:48,649
Neuroscientists pretty much always use cats' eyes for their experiments.

455
00:14:48,649 --> 00:14:51,320
So, that's why in a lot of educational content about computer vision,

456
00:14:51,320 --> 00:14:53,340
love to use cats as examples.

457
00:14:53,340 --> 00:14:54,980
And it's not just because their eyes are big.

458
00:14:54,980 --> 00:14:58,390
Or maybe it's because our real-life "Hakimi" also played a huge role in this.

459
00:14:58,390 --> 00:15:00,970
and helped kick-start our understanding of neural networks.

460
00:15:00,970 --> 00:15:03,570
So, what's the basic principle we use in neural networks?

461
00:15:03,570 --> 00:15:05,370
It acts as a small filter,

462
00:15:05,370 --> 00:15:06,950
or a small detector.

463
00:15:06,950 --> 00:15:08,620
And we call this a convolution kernel.

464
00:15:08,620 --> 00:15:10,500
And what's inside it is really just a bunch of numbers.

465
00:15:10,500 --> 00:15:11,980
For example, let's say I want to identify vertical lines.

466
00:15:11,980 --> 00:15:13,790
so that they're all the same for the vertical ones.

467
00:15:13,790 --> 00:15:15,430
This is a 3x3 matrix of numbers.

468
00:15:15,430 --> 00:15:17,510
We'll have it move from the top-left corner all the way over here.

469
00:15:17,510 --> 00:15:20,040
and just keep letting the convolution kernel scan across it.

470
00:15:20,040 --> 00:15:22,340
And with each scan, it's interacting with the image itself.

471
00:15:22,340 --> 00:15:25,240
Because, as we know, every single pixel has its own...

472
00:15:25,240 --> 00:15:26,660
and that number represents the pixel's color intensity.

473
00:15:26,660 --> 00:15:29,530
Let's have them perform a convolution operation.

474
00:15:29,530 --> 00:15:32,610
This mathematical operation is known as convolution.

475
00:15:32,610 --> 00:15:35,290
So, this scanning process is essentially what happens after we perform the convolution operation.

476
00:15:35,290 --> 00:15:36,310
into a single number.

477
00:15:36,310 --> 00:15:37,630
So, for this number...

478
00:15:37,630 --> 00:15:40,960
So, each of these convolution kernels represents a specific pattern.

479
00:15:40,960 --> 00:15:42,800
For example, one might represent the ability to recognize vertical lines.

480
00:15:42,800 --> 00:15:45,120
If it detects a larger number,

481
00:15:45,120 --> 00:15:46,960
it will make this section appear brighter.

482
00:15:46,960 --> 00:15:48,120
But if the number is smaller,

483
00:15:48,120 --> 00:15:49,780
it will make the corresponding area slightly darker.

484
00:15:49,780 --> 00:15:50,520
a high response

485
00:15:50,520 --> 00:15:54,470
This is just like the visual neurons we saw earlier in a cat's brain.

486
00:15:54,470 --> 00:15:55,870
The process is very similar.

487
00:15:55,870 --> 00:15:57,110
So, with this particular feature,

488
00:15:57,110 --> 00:16:00,000
Of course, we can use a whole lot of these convolutional kernels.

489
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:02,020
to scan the image over and over again.

490
00:16:02,020 --> 00:16:02,980
And as we all know,

491
00:16:02,980 --> 00:16:06,100
As we know, a color image is made up of three channels: RGB, right?

492
00:16:06,100 --> 00:16:08,260
So, we'd basically scan through this image three times.

493
00:16:08,260 --> 00:16:09,460
But in reality, mathematically speaking,

494
00:16:09,460 --> 00:16:11,520
It's a computation on a three-dimensional matrix.

495
00:16:11,520 --> 00:16:13,420
Actually, it doesn't even need three passes; it can be computed in just one.

496
00:16:13,420 --> 00:16:16,140
But for our purposes, we can understand it as operating on the three channels,

497
00:16:16,140 --> 00:16:19,140
the computation is performed by scanning through the R, G, and B channels separately.

498
00:16:19,140 --> 00:16:20,640
And after the calculation is done,

499
00:16:20,640 --> 00:16:23,360
So, it takes this image, an image of a little cat,

500
00:16:23,360 --> 00:16:25,600
Then, in the first layer, it gets transformed into something like this.

501
00:16:25,600 --> 00:16:27,320
Showing us which areas are sensitive to vertical lines.

502
00:16:27,320 --> 00:16:28,560
and which parts are not sensitive to vertical lines.

503
00:16:28,560 --> 00:16:30,170
So, for example, let's say...

504
00:16:30,170 --> 00:16:32,250
So we can interpret this area as having no vertical lines.

505
00:16:32,250 --> 00:16:34,510
this section might have a lot of vertical lines.

506
00:16:34,510 --> 00:16:36,470
And we call this the feature map.

507
00:16:36,470 --> 00:16:37,480
Feature map.

